AGI - 8 other alleged Israeli intelligence agents were arrested today in Istanbul under Operation "Talpa 3". This is the fourth Turkish anti-spionage operation against Mossad >active elements in Turkey since 7 October, the beginning of the Middle East conflict. Turkish President Recep Tayyip Erdogan> had secured 'zero tolerance' towards elements of Israeli intelligence services operating on the ground of his country. Words that followed the facts, before today 14 suspects had been arrested in two different operations, while last December 34 suspected Israeli agents were arrested.
&nbsp;
According to Ankara's security forces, suspects ended in the investigation network are Turkish or foreign citizens, never Israelis, to whom Mossad provides training often in Eastern Europe and then pays in cash, cryptocurrency or through foreign accounts.
&nbsp;
The accusation, for all alleged agents who have ended up in handcuffs in recent months, is to sell to Mossad information regarding Palestinian citizens, who are followed, pawned, approached. The collection of information also covers commercial activities in the hands of Palestinian citizens. The details of the operation of the Turkish forces remained long in silence and only recently began to be revealed. Israel for years has recruited and trained foreign citizens, almost all from Middle Eastern countries, to follow, take pictures and gather information and threaten dissidents and Palestinian civilians residing in Turkey.»
&nbsp;
Anonymous sources of the Mit told the Turkish media that there are two profiles on which the Turkish counter-spionage is concentrated: spies resident in Turkey who are assigned routine and operational tasks that come to the country where they stop for a limited amount of time with specific tasks. Based on what is known by local media, which cites an internal source to Turkish security services, intelligence activities have become more intense since October 7 and the flow of information to a division called "Operating Intelligence Service Center" has increased considerably since the same date. An increase in the activities > which has enabled several Israeli agents to be identified.
&nbsp;
The most striking cases concern the arrest last month, of Hamza Turan Ayberk>, former police commissioner, then became private investigator and character TV security expert. The man has repeatedly used his office, his means as an investigator and also involved his collaborators in tracking and positioning of spyware and bedbugs, without ever revealing that Mossad was the recipient of the collection of information. Ayberk in 2019 flew to Serbia, Belgrade, where he received training from Israeli agents. The rescue more similar to that of a spy film took place in Malaysia, where Palestinian hacker Omar A., resident in Turkey and for some time in the sight of Israel, went on holiday in September 2022.
&nbsp;
An unwise choice according to Turkish services, which decided to install a software to track Omar through the phone. A few days after the arrival in the capital Kuala Lumpur the young hacker was taken by Mossad agents, who took him to an abandoned place 50 kilometers from the capital. According to what was later revealed by media close to the government, Israeli agents questioned and tortured Omar, asking him to reveal details of unbridled cyber attacks against the Israeli defense system Iron Dome in the previous years.
&nbsp;
According to the Turkish media, the interview was attended by Mossad members, in a video connection from Tel Aviv. The Mit's men intervened. At first Ankara contacted the Malaysian security services, while the Mit, thanks to the software installed in the phone, managed to geolocalize kidnapped and abducted. Once the position was communicated to the authorities of Kuala Lumpur, Malaysian special forces entered into action. The hacker was released and 11 elements of the Mossad arrested.
&nbsp;
Omar returned to Turkey, where there were men of the Mit who set him up in a house where he would be safe. The Turkish media report that the attention of the intelligence of Ankara is currently concentrated on a man whose codename is MZ, considered a former bodyguard of Khaled Meshal>, one of Hamas' political leaders who is often in Turkey. MZ was not arrested and Turkish services are on his tracks.

